The purpose of my project is to observe the trend of average global surface temperatures

It is commonly known that the average global temperature is directly correlated to global warming hence forecasting temperatures 10 years from now may provide insight into the rapidly changing state of the world. To do this I will be using a forecasting tool called Prophet, created by Meta.

https://facebook.github.io/prophet/docs/quick_start.html#r-api - Guide on Meta

library("prophet")
library(readxl)
Monthly_Average_Temp <- read_excel("~/Downloads/Monthly Average Temp.xlsx")
Averagetemperature.dataframe <- data.frame(
  ds = as.Date(Monthly_Average_Temp$Date), 
  y = Monthly_Average_Temp$'Monthly Mean Temperature' 
)

First, I called the function library which contains the forecasting tool, prophet. Because I used my own data set, I had to call it from an external excel file. I then stored the data set in the variable Monthly_Average_Temp. Following this, I created the data frame called Averagetemperature.dataframe. My dates from my dataset are then assigned to the date stamp called ds and my average global temperatures are assigned to y representing the data that I want to be forecasted.

average_model = prophet::prophet(Averagetemperature.dataframe, changepoint.prior.scale = 0.05, weekly.seasonality = TRUE, daily.seasonality = TRUE)

The prophet function is called again and a forecasting model is created using the dates and historical data stored in Averagetemperature.dataframe. The change point scale changes the flexibility in the change point. Change point is the point where there is a significant change (spike) in the data points which will be shown more clearly in the graphs later on.

future_year = prophet::make_future_dataframe(average_model, periods=15, freq="year")
tail(future_year)
##             ds
## 334 2026-12-01
## 335 2027-12-01
## 336 2028-12-01
## 337 2029-12-01
## 338 2030-12-01
## 339 2031-12-01
future_month = prophet::make_future_dataframe(average_model, periods=36, freq="month")
tail(future_month)
##             ds
## 355 2019-07-01
## 356 2019-08-01
## 357 2019-09-01
## 358 2019-10-01
## 359 2019-11-01
## 360 2019-12-01

These next few lines of code will create a new data frame storing future dates. I had a little mess around with the different frequencies to see how the forecast displayed on the graph can change. The periods give me the authority to set how long I want the data to be predicted for. I personally chose 15 years for one and 36 months for the other. I added the function tail to display the last 6 dates of the forecast. This is only really useful for post-analysis of the results.

prediction_year = predict(average_model,future_year)
prediction_month = predict(average_model, future_month)

The predict function is important since this creates the future data values which will be assigned to their corresponding future dates. Essentially this completes the forecast and all that’s now left to do is to plot the data.

This next piece of code now plots the historical and future data points within the time frame I selected, specified in my code earlier.

Yearly Plot

plot(average_model,prediction_year) + add_changepoints_to_plot(average_model)

dyplot.prophet(average_model, prediction_year)

The frequency of this graph is set to year and shows the yearly change in average global temperatures. I wanted this graph to forecast the next 15 years.

Monthly Plot

plot(average_model,prediction_month) + add_changepoints_to_plot(average_model)

dyplot.prophet(average_model, prediction_month)

The frequency for this graph is set to month and this graph shows the monthly change in average global temperatures. I wanted this graph to plot 36 months of future data at smaller intervals than the yearly graph.

Change points are also added to signify large jumps between my data. These can give insight as to whether some external event has occurred causing the global average temperature to rise. The most likely cause of this is human involvement and is explained later in the article.

dyplot.prophet is very useful because it allows a viewer to interact with the graph and at a certain point you are able to view the future values for example, you are able to check the average global temperature in 2026 if you are interested simply by hovering over the graph.

Seasonality

prophet_plot_components(average_model,prediction_year)

This shows the daily, weekly and yearly seasonality. It also shows the overall trend of the three graphs.

Describing the Trend

As seen from the graphs provided, the average global surface temperature of the earth is predicted to rise at a fairly constant rate and the date and average temperature is positively correlated. This is backed up by the trend for seasonality being a linear positive correlation as well. This indicates that global warming may be rising as a result of several factors. One major factor is increased greenhouse emissions. As we become more industrialized, we release more harmful gases which eventually harm the atmosphere. Another significant sign pointing to this is that the change points all lie around 2010.

https://climate.nasa.gov/news/467/nasa-research-finds-2010-tied-for-warmest-year-on-record/

As stated in this article, NASA recorded record high global temperatures in 2010 compared to the last 20 years. The clear trend seen on every graph is that global temperatures are very volatile but have seen steady growth. The hottest day recorded in my data was March 2016 at 1.22 degrees Celsius compared to 2010’s hottest day which was roughly 0.62 degrees Celsius.

I think seasonality plays a large role in average global temperatures rising but not as big as expected. As seen in the daily graph, the average temperature rises by 0.01 degrees Celsius from 02:00 to 22:00 before dropping by -0.02 degrees Celsius. This can be explained by natural phenomena since at night it gets colder and throughout the day it get warmer gradually. As a result, smaller time intervals may not be a useful indicator as to whether average temperatures are rising.

https://www.climate.gov/news-features/climate-qa/hasnt-earth-warmed-and-cooled-naturally-throughout-history#

This article states that the Earth may be naturally warming anyway. So it is better to look at longer time periods as well the extreme data values (outliers).

Points of Interest

Interestingly, in January the global average temperature rises as shown in the monthly seasonality graph. This is strange because before and after January (December and February to March) the average temperatures are the lowest in the entire year.

There are several outliers on the dyplot. One such outlier is March 2016 which had an average global temperature of 1.19 degrees whereas the average in 2016 was about 0.85 degrees. The reason 2016 is unique is because it had about 5 outliers in a very short time period all above 1 degrees Celsius. I would have thought this would skew the predicted data but it seems the data is fairly linear. One downside with my predicted data values is that it doesn’t account for extreme data values past 2016 which most often than not happen on an annual basis as confirmed by the graphs.
